<HEAD>Montana Candidates Brace for Expensive Fall Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Max Baucus and his Democratic
supporters say they're bracing for an avalanche of Republican cash
in this fall's general election battle with Lt. Gov. Allen Kolstad.
   But Baucus, a two-term Democrat who was nominated for re-election
Tuesday, has his own pile of campaign cash, which Republicans are
trying to turn into a liability rather than an asset.
   ``Senator Baucus will learn the hard way that Montana cannot be
bought with an out-of-state war chest,'' said Montana GOP Chairman
Barbara Campbell. ``Does he need $2 million to get re-elected to a
job he's held for 12 years? That says he's very weak.''
   Baucus coasted past two primary opponents Tuesday with 83 percent
of the Democratic vote, while Kolstad won a four-man race with 43
percent of the GOP vote.
   Kolstad and the Republicans are hoping for a repeat of 1988, when
upstart Republican Conrad Burns pulled off an upset victory over
two-term incumbent Democratic Sen. John Melcher.
   Kolstad promised Wednesday to run an above-board campaign
focusing on economic issues and refraining from personal attacks.
But Democratic Party Chairman Bruce Nelson said he expects Kolstad
to go on the offensive against Baucus.
   ``The pattern that Republicans set two years ago of a relentless
negative attack is the same thing that they will do this year,'' he
predicted.
   Baucus already has raised more than $2 million in campaign funds,
smashing the state campaign-spending record of $1.2 million set by
Melcher in 1988.
</TEXT>
