<HEAD>New Allegations in Lawsuit Against Montana GOP, National
Republican Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB ANEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former executive director of the
Montana Republican Party has accused the organization, its
chairwoman and a national GOP committee of breaking federal
racketeering laws.
   The allegations involved the handling of political money during
the 1988 campaigns.
   Terry Merica made the allegations in a complaint filed in U.S.
District Court on Wednesday. It amends a lawsuit he and his wife,
Neida, filed in December.
   The complaint alleges that the state GOP, Chairwoman Barbara
Campbell and the National Republican Senatorial Committee committed
wire and mail fraud by illegally funneling money into the campaigns
of Sen. Conrad Burns and Gov. Stan Stephens.
   Burns, at the time a county commissioner in Billings, upset
Democratic incumbent Sen. John Melcher in the November election.
Stephens defeated former Democratic Gov. Tom Judge in the race for
governor.
   The complaint says the defendants used a series of letters and
money transfers in the spring and summer of 1988 to defraud the
citizens of Montana and the United States.
   The original lawsuit alleged the Mericas were fired in late 1988
for questioning whether financial dealings between the state
Republican Party and the national committee violated state and
federal election laws.
   Neida Merica was an administrative secretary for the state GOP.
   Wednesday's complaint contends there were additional violations
of the federal Racketeer Influenced, Corrupt Organizations Act.
   Charles Erdmann, attorney for the Montana GOP, said the new
contentions may reflect Merica's concern that the original suit
will be dismissed.
   ``This may be nothing more than an attempt to bolster their
complaint,'' he said.
   He would not comment on specifics, saying he had not seen the
new complaint, but he questioned the timing of its filing. The
state GOP convention began Thursday in Billings, with President
Bush scheduled to appear in the evening on behalf of Lt. Gov. Allen
Kolstad, who is challenging Democratic incumbent Sen. Max Baucus.
   ``The timing of this would make you think this is politically
motivated,'' Campbell said Thursday.
   James Goetz, the Mericas' attorney, said the timing was
coincidence.
   The National Republican Senatorial Committee, which helps
organize campaigns of GOP Senate candidates, had no immediate
comment on the new allegations.
   The complaint alleges the defendants committed mail and wire
fraud by not legally reporting as much as $200,000 in campaign
contributions in 1988.
   It cites several instances of questionable handling of campaign
financing. It alleges that:
   _The national committee conducted a voter identification project
in Montana, but gave results only to the Burns and Stephens
campaigns. The cost of the project was never reported as a
contribution to the campaigns and the expense exceeded the federal
limit on what such committees can give to a candidate.
   _The national committee transferred thousands of dollars through
the Montana GOP's accounts to help pay for a direct mailing by a
Texas company for the Burns campaign in violation of federal
election laws.
   _Between Aug. 8, 1988, and Nov. 16, 1988, the national committee
shifted $178,145 into the Montana GOP's account. The money
transfers prompted a Nov. 8 memo from Ward Shanahan, the state
party's lawyer, to GOP headquarters warning that the national
committee was using the Montana Republican Party for ``financial
shenanigans.''
   _In October 1988, the Republican Governors' Association gave
$8,000 to the Montana GOP with a letter from Executive Director
Michele Davis saying the money should be reported as coming from
the Republican National Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

