<BYLINE>By BOB ANEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gov. Allen Kolstad on Tuesday defeated
three fellow Republicans for the right to challenge Sen. Max Baucus
in a bid to repeat the GOP's 1988 feat of knocking off a Democratic
incumbent.
   Baucus, seeking his third term, had no trouble turning back a
challenge for the Democratic nomination from John Driscoll, a Public
Service Commission member, and evangelist Curly Thornton.
   With 694 of 967 precincts reporting, Kolstad had 27,250 votes, or
42 percent, to 23,352 votes, or 36 percent, for businessman and
scientist Bruce Vorhauer; 8,569 votes, or 13 percent for state Sen.
Bill Farrell; and 4,981 votes, or 8 percent, for former business
executive John Domenech.
   In the Democratic race, Baucus had 61,054 votes, or 83 percent,
to 9,538 votes for Driscoll, or 13 percent, and 3,192 votes for
Thornton, or 4 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Senate race was the only major contest on the Montana ballot.
Republicans are hoping for a replay this fall of the 1988 general
election, when Conrad Burns, a relatively unknown county
commissioner from Billings, toppled veteran Democratic Sen. John
Melcher.
   National Republicans, including President Bush and former
President Ronald Reagan, searched for a well-known Republican to
challenge Baucus. They recruited Kolstad, 58, who became lieutenant
governor only 17 months ago.
   Kolstad emphasized his farming background, his 20 years in the
state Legislature and his lifelong ties to Montana. The emphasis
also was a slap at Vorhauer, who moved his legal residence to
Montana only last fall.
   Vorhauer, 48, is best known as the inventor of the Today
contraceptive sponge. His campaign stressed his engineering and
science background as qualifying him to bring high-tech businesses
to the state.
   Farrell, 41, a trucking company owner, touted his working-man
image. Domenech, 36, campaigned for a national health plan.
   Baucus ran a quiet primary campaign, with neither of his
challengers having much money or elaborate organizations. Baucus has
raised about $2 million, citing the Republican challenge he will
face this fall.
</TEXT>
