<HEAD>Melcher Ousted From Senate, GOP's Stephens Wins Governor Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two-term Democratic U.S. Sen. John Melcher
lost to a Republican county commissioner and Republicans captured
the Montana governor's mansion after 20 years of Democratic control.
   Republican George Bush won the state's four electoral votes.
   Conrad Burns, a commissioner from Montana's most populous county
which includes Billings, became the first GOP senator from Montana
in 36 years.
   Burns said taxes and the Montana wilderness bill sponsored by
Melcher but vetoed last week by President Reagan were keys to his
victory Tuesday.
   ``The 101st Congress is really going to have to knuckle down and
go to work on this deficit,'' he said.
   Melcher said he'd only been campaigning for about 18 days and ``I
never really had a good feel for the race.''
   With 98 percent of the precincts reporting, Burns had 184,789, or
52 percent, and Melcher, 170,149, or 48 percent.
   In the governor's race, Republican Stan Stephens, a former state
senator, defeated former Democrat Gov. Tom Judge, who was seeking
his third term after losing in his party's primary eight years ago
to retiring Gov. Ted Schwinden.
   ``I'd like to think we won the contest because people realize we
represent change,'' said Stephens, a Canadian immigrant who came to
Montana to harvest wheat 39 years ago.
   Stephens had 185,256 votes, 53 percent, to Judge's 164,111 votes,
47 percent.
   Bush collected 185,688 for 53 percent, Democrat Michael Dukakis
had 163,507 for 47 percent.
   Montana's two congressmen, a Republican and a Democrat, were
re-elected.
</TEXT>
