<HEAD>LaserPhoto Covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Dianne Feinstein and John Van de Kamp brawled to the wire for one
of 1990's biggest political prizes, the Democratic nomination for
governor of California, and voters set lineups Tuesday for fall
contests in eight other states.
   The busiest primary night so far this campaign year saw North
Carolina Democrats deciding whether former Charlotte Mayor Harvey
Gantt or county prosecutor Mike Easley would get the formidable task
of challenging Republican Sen. Jesse Helms.
   Gantt was bidding to become the first black nominated for U.S.
Senate in North Carolina this century.
   ``I'm ready to get into this fight'' with Helms, Gantt said as he
cast his own ballot. ``I'm ready to get it on with him.''
   Feinstein, the former mayor of San Francisco, and Van de Kamp,
the state attorney general, have spent millions of dollars battling
each other and now the winner will plunge into an even more costly
and just as nasty general election race against Republican Sen. Pete
Wilson. He is trying to keep the California governor's office in GOP
control.
   Voters also were choosing nominees in New Jersey, Alabama, Iowa,
South Dakota, Montana, New Mexico, and Mississippi.
   As usual, California voters also were making decisions on ballot
propositions, including two that would strip the legislature of most
of its power to redraw legislative, including congressional,
district lines. California is likely to gain six U.S. House seats as
a result of the 1990 Census.
   Another California ballot proposal would double the gasoline tax
over the next five years and was being watched as a signal of a
shift in sentiment in the state where the anti-tax revolt began in
the 1970s.
   Seven senators and three governors were on ballots, none with
serious primary opposition.
   The senators were Democrats Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Howell
Heflin of Alabama, Max Baucus of Montana and Tom Harkin of Iowa. The
Republicans were Larry Pressler of South Dakota, Pete Domenici of
New Mexico and Thad Cochran of Mississippi.
   Long in advance of their formal nomination in the primary, Harkin
and Republican Rep. Tom Tauke began campaigning against each other
in what looks like one of the tightest Senate races of the year.
   Alabama Republican Bill Cabannis was geared to challenge Heflin
and Democrat Ted Muenster was taking on Pressler in South Dakota.
   In Montana, Lt. Gov. Allen Kolstad and businessman Bruce Vorhauer
were the leading contenders for the Republican nomination to
challenge Baucus.
   Scores of primaries also were deciding the lineups for elections
to the House. One incumbent who faced a strong challenge was
Democratic Rep. Jim Bates of San Diego, who was rebuked by the House
Ethics Committee for sexual harassment of women employees.
   One of the hottest primaries for a congressional seat was in the
New Jersey district represented by James Courter, the unsuccessful
GOP candidate for governor in 1989. Courter is not seeking
re-election to the House and the Republican contenders to succeed
him include Assemblyman Rodney Frelinghuysen, state Sen. Richard A.
Zimmer and professional football player Phil McConkey.
   Marguerite Chandler was unopposed for the Democratic nomination.
   Gov. Guy Hunt of Alabama, the first Republican elected to that
office this century, was bidding for a second term and a crowded
field of Democrats was vying to challenge him.
   Former Gov. Fob James, educator-lobbyist Paul Hubbert, Rep.
Ronnie Flippo, and Attorney General Don Siegelman were the leading
contenders. No one was expected to get the clear majority needed to
avoid a June 26 runoff.
   In a race in which abortion was a major issue, Iowa Democrats
were choosing among Attorney General Tom Miller, House Speaker Don
Avenson and banker John Chrystal for the nomination to challenge
Republican Gov. Terry Branstad.
   Avenson and Chrystal support the pro-choice position, while
Miller and Branstad are abortion opponents.
   Republican Gov. Garrey Carruthers of New Mexico was ineligible to
seek re-election. Four Democrats, including former Gov. Bruce King,
and four Republicans were competing to succeed him. The next
governor will be the first allowed to serve two consecutive
four-year terms.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   South Dakota Gov. George Mickelson had no GOP primary opposition
as he seeks a second term. In November he will face former
Democratic state Sen. Bob Samuelson.
   Contrary to political tradition, President Bush and other top GOP
officials have not hesitated this year to intervene in party
primaries on behalf of candidates they believe would run strongest
against Democrats in the fall.
   The White House helped persuade Wilson _ who didn't need much
persuading _ to enter the California governor's race a year after he
won a $13 million campaign for re-election to the Senate.
   Control of the governor's office in California is the highest
priority for the leaders of both national parties.
   After the 1980 Census, Democrats had complete control of the
redistricting process in the state and Republicans claim it cost
them at least five U.S. House seats.
   Wilson already has $3.5 million in his campaign bank account and
there is speculation the GOP will spend close to $20 million in the
race to succeed Republican Gov. George Deukmejian, who decided
against seeking a third term.
   The White House recruited Kolstad to take on Baucus in Montana,
but the effort backfired when three other Republicans also entered
the race.
   The latest round of primaries saw no change in the issues mix
that has marked other races this year. Nor was there any diminution
in the negative tone of campaign commercials.
   The roughest rhetoric was in the Feinstein-Van de Kamp race and
it left some Democrats concerned about prospects for uniting the
party in time for the fall campaign.
   The death penalty, abortion and the environment were common
themes.
   In Iowa, the National Abortion Rights Action League endorsed
Avenson out of concern that a Democratic primary victory by Miller
would mean the choice in November would be between two abortion foes.
   Feinstein and Van de Kamp argued over which was more reliably
pro-choice.
   Van de Kamp campaigned over the weekend with Norma McCorvey, who
was the ``Jane Roe'' in the Supreme Court's landmark abortion
decision. McCorvey endorsed the California attorney general because
``I trust John Van de Kamp to defend the right I fought so hard to
win.''
   Feinstein countered that as a woman she would be the most
reliable guardian of the pro-choice position.
</TEXT>
