<HEAD>Incumbent Montana Senator Crushes GOP Opponent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Sen. Max Baucus said he prepared
for a tough race, but ended up with a pushover, downing Republican
Allen Kolstad by a better than 2-to-1 margin.
   With 92 percent of precincts reporting, Baucus had 201,489
votes, or 70 percent. Kolstad, Montana's lieutenant governor, had
85,787, or 30 percent.
   Baucus returns to Washington for his third term. He said he
focused his campaign on convincing voters he was working to lessen
unemployment.
   Kolstad said he ran a hard, honest campaign but was outgunned by
Baucus' $3 million campaign fund. Kolstad also castigated Baucus
for running a deceptive campaign.
   Meanwhile, Montana voters on Tuesday defeated an initiative that
would have increased cigarette taxes by 25 cents a pack. Voters
also re-elected the state's incumbent congressmen - one Democrat
and one Republican.
</TEXT>
