<HL> Politics &amp; Policy -- Campaign '88: Status Quo Was Big Winner in Tuesday Election With Trend of Divided Government Continuing </HL>
<AUTHOR> James M. Perry and John E. Yang (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<G> EXE CNG </G>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The big winner Tuesday was the status quo. 

   Vice President George Bush succeeded his mentor, President Ronald Reagan. 
Of 408 incumbents seeking re-election to the House, 99% will be back. 
In the Senate, in the face of Mr. Bush's triumph over Democrat Michael Dukakis, a single incumbent Democrat was defeated while the Republicans lost three incumbents. 

   At the state level, the Democrats picked up one governorship -- they now outnumber the Republicans 28 to 22 -- and hung on to almost all of their legislative seats, even in the Deep South, where Mr. Bush crushed Mr. Dukakis. 

   It's the same old story. 
Republicans win the White House -- this was their fifth victory in the past six elections -- and Democrats hold on to the House and the Senate, most of the governorships and most of the state legislatures. 
Divided government is becoming an American institution. 

   One reason for Mr. Bush's decisive victory -- he piled up almost 54% of the popular vote and won 426 out of 538 electoral votes -- was a growing sense of optimism about the nation's economy, according to a Wall Street Journal/NBC News national voter poll. 
In the election-day poll, 28% of the respondents said they expected the economy to improve next year (and 16% thought it would get worse). 
This was a big jump from recent Journal/NBC News telephone polls, in which only about 19% felt optimistic about the economy. 

   Men, much more than women, believed in the good news about the economy, and that led to the so-called gender gap. 
Mr. Bush was supported by more than half of the men surveyed but less than half of the women. 

   Mr. Reagan won his great landslides with an outpouring of votes from young people. 
But Mr. Bush, despite reaching out to the "baby boomers" with his selection of 41-year-old Dan Quayle as his running mate, barely broke even with voters from 25 to 42 years old. 
Mr. Bush had a slight edge in the Journal/NBC poll. 
But among even younger voters -- those between 18 and 24 -- Mr. Dukakis held a narrow edge. 

   There was more encouraging news for the Democrats. 
According to the Journal/NBC poll, six out of 10 Democrats who voted for Mr. Reagan four years ago came home to vote for Mr. Dukakis. 
Nine out of 10 blacks stuck with the Democratic ticket (though it wasn't clear how high the black turnout was). 
Among Roman Catholics, Mr. Dukakis maintained a narrow lead, reversing the GOP advantage in recent elections. 
Among Jewish voters, he led better than two to one, while Mr. Bush led among Protestants. 

   By carrying 10 states and the District of Columbia, Mr. Dukakis did better than Walter Mondale in 1984 (one state and the District of Columbia) and President Jimmy Carter in 1980 (six states and the always reliable District of Columbia). 

   Frustrating to the Democrats is how tantalizingly close they came in 11 other states, where they picked up 46% or more of the vote. 
These states include California, Illinois, Connecticut, Michigan and Missouri. 
If Mr. Dukakis had won all 11 of these states, he would have eked out a narrow electoral-college victory. 

   In the Senate, where turnovers occur much more frequently than in the House and where the Republicans had control from 1980 to 1986, the Democrats actually gained one or two seats. 

   The big shocker was Connecticut, where three-term incumbent Lowell Weicker was upset by Democrat Joe Lieberman. 
Two other GOP incumbents -- Chic Hecht of Nevada and David Karnes of Nebraska -- were defeated by, respectively, Gov. Richard Bryan and former Gov. Robert Kerrey. 

   In another upset, Democrat John Melcher of Montana was defeated by former farm broadcaster Conrad Burns. 
Closest of all is the Florida Senate race between Democratic Rep. Buddy MacKay and Republican Rep. Connie Mack, which may be decided by the absentee ballots that are still to be counted. 

   Republican hopes that Mr. Bush might have coattails never were realized in House races. 
In a swing district in New Jersey, for example, Democrats retained the seat held by the late Rep. James Howard. 
And in North Carolina's 11th district, the most competitive in the nation, Democratic Rep. James McClure Clarke beat Republican Charles Taylor to become the first incumbent to be returned from that district since 1978. 

   Democrats did well in contests for open House seats. 
They held onto a district in southeast Florida as Democrat Harry Johnston easily defeated Republican Ken Adams after a hard-fought campaign. 
Democrats also won House seats being given up by Republicans in Nebraska and Texas. 

   Most of the incumbents turned out on Tuesday were mired in scandal, notably House Banking Committee Chairman Fernand St Germain, a Rhode Island Democrat who had been investigated for allegedly accepting favors from a savings-and-loan lobbyist. 

   Georgia Republican Rep. Patrick Swindall, under indictment for his participation in a federal drug-money sting, was easily defeated by Democrat Ben Jones, who played the character "Cooter" in the television series "The Dukes of Hazzard." 

   Other House members touched by scandal were locked in tight races. 
Democrats Roy Dyson of Maryland and Bill Chappell of Florida, both implicated in the Pentagon procurement scandal, held razor-thin leads in races that could be decided by absentee ballots. 
Similarly, New York Republican Joseph DioGuardi, under fire for accepting $50,000 in allegedly illegal campaign contributions, was trailing his Democratic opponent in a close contest that could also turn on absentee voters. 

   The most important of these races was the defeat of Rep. St Germain, a 14-term veteran and the first House committee chairman to be turned out since 1980. 
Next in line for his job is the eccentric Rep. Henry Gonzalez of Texas, who has had little legislative impact in his 26-year House career. 
While he doesn't seem to get much respect among rank-and-file Democrats, he is likely to have the backing of House Speaker James Wright, a fellow Texan. 
In addition, Mr. Gonzalez's colleagues may find it difficult to reject one of the few senior Hispanic members of Congress. 

   Rep. Frank Annunzio, a rough-hewn Chicago machine pol who is the third-ranking committee member, is in frail health and isn't likely to seek the chairmanship. 
Others down the seniority line eyeing the post include Del. 
Walter Fauntroy of the District of Columbia and Reps. 
Stephen Neal of North Carolina, Mary Rose Oakar of Ohio and John LaFalce and Charles Schumer, both of New York. 

   In the 12 governors' races Tuesday, Democrats registered a net gain of one statehouse, increasing their margin over the Republicans to 28 to 22. 

   The big win for the Democrats took place in Indiana, where Evan Bayh, son of former U.S. Sen. Birch Bayh, defeated Republican Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz, 53% to 47%. 
Mr. Bayh becomes the state's first Democratic governor in 20 years. 
His father was defeated for re-election to the Senate in 1980 by a young Republican, Dan Quayle. 

   In West Virginia, veteran Republican Gov. Arch Moore was denied an unprecedented fourth term in office when he was defeated by Democrat Gaston Caperton, an insurance executive. 

   In Montana, the Democratic candidate, former Gov. Thomas Judge, was upset by Republican state Sen. Stan Stephens, ending a long Democratic reign. 

   Democrats held their own in state legislative races too, where they already held a 4,445 to 2,923 lead over the Republicans. 
Maintaining this lead carries an important political advantage, as state legislatures prepare to reapportion congressional seats in 1991 following the 1990 census. 
Republicans have long contended that one reason the Democrats hang on to the House is that, decade after decade, they gerrymander the districts to their advantage. 

   Fragmented returns indicated the Republicans failed to make any gains in legislative seats, a turnaround for them in light of Republican gains of more than 300 seats in 1980 and again in 1984. 

   Democrats remain in control of both chambers in 28 states and control one of the two chambers in 13 more. 
The Republicans control both chambers in eight states. 
The Nebraska Legislature is unicameral and nonpartisan. 

   On Tuesday, the Democrats picked up control of the house in Montana and the senate in New Mexico and lost the house in Vermont. 
The Democrats lost 13 house seats in North Carolina, their biggest setback and possibly an omen of what is in store for them in the South, and lost some ground in Ohio and Michigan. 

