<HEAD>Crowded Governor's Field Tops Montana June 7 Primary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB ANEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Montana's race for governor, rocked by the
sudden withdrawal of the incumbent and the unexpected death of his
chief opponent, has left the state with a jumble of more candidates
than it has seen in 16 years.
   The remaining candidates in the June 7 primary include Montana's
attorney general, who is trying to overcome a drunken-driving
conviction; a former governor; a former state Supreme Court
justice; three past and present legislators; a drug
addict-turned-preacher and a tax protester.
   Democratic Gov. Ted Schwinden's decision last summer not to seek
a third term, saying he wanted concentrate more on his farm and
family, opened doors for candidates who had been unwilling to take
on the popular incumbent.
   Then, in early April, a plane crash killed the Republican
front-runner, Secretary of State Jim Waltermire, leaving his
supporters with a dilemma over which of the two remaining GOP
contenders to back.
   The common thread running through the eight-man campaign for
governor, the most crowded since 1972, has been economic
development, with the candidates offering ideas for infusing new
life into Montana's lackluster economy.
   The two Republican candidates, former state Sen. Stan Stephens
and state Rep. Cal Winslow, are vying for the chance to end the
Democratic Party's 20-year reign in the governor's chair.
   Both men have legislative backgrounds; Stephens has logged 16
years in the Senate and Winslow has served eight years in House.
But the similarities end there.
   Stephens, 58, has attracted support from the mainstream of the
state Republican Party, collecting support from former party
leaders and longtime GOP officeholders. He boasts of his experience
in Senate leadership positions and as a successful businessman from
northern Montana.
   Winslow, 38, has appealed to the younger elements of the
Republican Party, portraying himself as a conduit for attracting
new business to the state.
   The six Democratic candidates include three serious contenders.
   Thomas Judge, who was governor from 1973 to 1981, is attempting
a comeback after losing in the 1980 Democratic primary to
Schwinden. The 53-year-old investment adviser has built his
campaign on experience and an elaborate economic development plan.
   ``I won't need four years of on-the-job training,'' he has said,
boasting of the state's lucrative economy during his two terms as
governor.
   Attorney General Mike Greely, 48, overcame the stigma of a 1986
drunken-driving conviction to enter the race. He's called for a
more aggressive program for marketing Montana products elsewhere.
   Frank Morrison Jr., who resigned as a state Supreme Court
justice last year to run, has emerged as the candidate most
vehemently opposed to a retail sales tax.
   Seen as the most liberal of the Democrats, the 50-year-old
Morrison has political roots in Nebraska, where his father was a
three-term governor.
   The other Democratic candidates are Ted Neuman, a little-known
state senator and farmer; Emmett ``Curly'' Thornton, a traveling
evangelist who preaches on the dangers of alcohol and drug abuse
based on his own past addictions; and Martin ``Red'' Beckman, a tax
protester and author.
</TEXT>
