<TEXT>
   Here is a look at the closest races, starting with Senate
contests:
   NORTH CAROLINA - Harvey Gantt, the black former mayor of
Charlotte, is giving Sen. Jesse Helms the toughest race of his
career. Independent polls say the race is a dead heat. Gantt and
Helms differ on just about every issue. The conservative Republican
senator depicts his challenger as ``an extremist'' who supports
late-term abortions and those for sex-selection. Gantt depicts
Helms as an ideologue who votes against the interests of his state,
particularly on education and the environment.
   IOWA - Democratic Sen. Tom Harkin is battling Rep. Tom Tauke as
well as an Iowa tradition of not re-electing Democratic senators.
Polls show Harkin consistently in the lead but his edge is often
well within the margin of error. Abortion is a major issue with
Harkin pro-choice and Tauke firmly opposed to abortion. Iowa bucked
a national trend in the 1980s and became one of the strongest
growth areas for the Democrats, a factor that could help Harkin in
a close race.
   OREGON - Republican Sen. Mark Hatfield, bidding for a fifth
term, may be the best example of a complacent incumbent. Democratic
businessman Harry Lonsdale hammered away at Hatfield for months and
the senator ignored the challenge until a recent poll showed
Lonsdale had climbed to within 6 points of the incumbent. Another
race in which abortion is an issue; Hatfield is opposed while
Lonsdale is a supporter.
   HAWAII - Generally regarded as the best chance for the
Republicans to pick up a Democratic seat. Democrat Daniel Akaka was
appointed to the Senate last summer after Spark Matsunaga died. A
lackluster campaigner who held a safe House seat for seven terms,
Akaka is opposed by Republican Rep. Pat Saiki. Even Hawaii
Democrats conceded that Saiki is a dynamic campaigner and has a
strong chance to win in this heavily Democratic state.
   MASSACHUSETTS - Sen. John Kerry was considered a shoo-in for
re-election in this heavily Democratic state until the voters
expressed their rage in the Sept. 18 primary. Suddenly, independent
polls said the race between Kerry and his Republican challenger,
Jim Rappaport, was a dead heat. A wealthy businessman prepared to
spend millions on the race, Rappaport is concentrating on linking
Kerry to the highly unpopular outgoing governor, Dukakis.
   RHODE ISLAND - Democrat Claiborne Pell was elected to the Senate
in 1960, the year John F. Kennedy was elected president. His six
terms have given him the seniority to become chairman of the
Foreign Relations Committee but have also made him vulnerable to a
challenge from 43-year-old Rep. Claudine Schneider. Politely but
firmly, Schneider suggests it is time for a younger person to take
Pell's seat. However, recent polls give Pell, 71, an 18-point lead.
   NEW HAMPSHIRE - GOP Rep. Bob Smith was heavily favored to
capture the Senate seat being vacated by fellow conservative Gordon
Humphrey. But former Sen. John Durkin has made a race of it and a
recent poll said Smith's 4-point lead was within the margin of
error.
   In other states, a large number of Senate contests looked
tempting to challengers but didn't seem to pan out. They include
Illinois where Democratic Sen. Paul Simon looks far ahead of
Republican Rep. Lynn Martin; Michigan where Democratic Sen. Carl
Levin is outdistancing Rep. Bill Schuette; Nebraska where
Democratic Sen. James Exon leads former Rep. Hal Daub; Kentucky
where Republican Sen. Mitch McConnell leads Harvey Sloane, and
Montana where Democratic Sen. Max Baucus is well ahead of Lt. Gov.
Allen Kolstad.
   Among the races for governor, these are getting the most
attention:
   CALIFORNIA - The battle between former San Francisco Mayor
Dianne Feinstein, the Democratic nominee, and GOP Sen. Pete Wilson
is generally regarded as the most important contest in the nation.
California is likely to pick up seven new House seats in 1992 and
if Feinstein wins her party will have total control of how the
lines are drawn in the nation's most populous state. A victory for
Wilson gives the GOP an important role although the legislature
will remain Democratic. Wilson and Feinstein agree on more issues
than they disagree. Wilson's lead in the polls is well within the
margin of error.
   TEXAS - Republican millionaire Clayton Williams seemed well on
his way to victory over Democrat Ann Richards. But last week a new
poll said Richards had moved to within 5 points of Williams, whose
repeated verbal gaffes may be cutting into his support.
   FLORIDA - Martinez got into trouble over taxes early in his
first term and then found his hard-line anti-abortion stand had
moved out of favor with voters. Former Sen. Lawton Chiles got into
the race and led in most polls. Recently the margin has narrowed
and Martinez has a big edge in money.
   Florida is one of the six states where GOP governors are
threatened. The others are Alabama, where Gov. Guy Hunt is leading
teachers union official Paul Hubbert; Nebraska, where Gov. Kay Orr
is trailing businessman Ben Nelson; Kansas, where Gov. Mike Hayden
and state treasurer Joan Finney were in a dead heat; Maine, where
former Democratic Gov. Joseph Brennan held a narrow lead over Gov.
John R. McKernan; and Rhode Island where Gov. Edward DiPrete was
running far behind businessman Bruce Sundlun.
   The best bets for Republican pickups were in Vermont, Alaska,
Massachusetts, Oregon, and Ohio. Democratic governors are not
running in each of those states.
   In Oklahoma, GOP Gov. Henry Bellmon is not running and Democrats
hope for another gain.
</TEXT>
