<HEAD>Boschwitz Leads Wellstone in Latest Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. Rudy Boschwitz has
increased his lead over challenger Paul Wellstone, according to a
poll published Saturday.
   The Pioneer Press-WCCO poll indicated that 49 percent of 760
likely voters polled last week preferred Boschwitz, while 40
percent favored Wellstone. Eleven percent were undecided, and the
margin of error was 4 percentage points.
   A Star Tribune-KSTP-TV Minnesota Poll published Oct. 24 showed a
closer race. That poll found that 48 percent of those questioned
chose Boschwitz compared with 45 percent for Wellstone. The margin
of error was 4 percentage points.
   Boschwitz has felt the backlash of voter discontent in the wake
of problems that plagued Republican gubernatorial hopeful Jon
Grunseth. Grunseth withdrew from the race after allegations that he
swam nude with teen-age girls in 1981.
   Democrat Wellstone began the campaign as a little-known college
professor and activist, but benefited from the Grunseth fallout.
Wellstone has tried to exploit a nationwide anti-incumbent mood.
   Boschwitz has labeled Wellstone a big-spending liberal whose
proposals would cost the taxpayers an additional $600 billion a
year and derail federal budget-balancing efforts.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Chiles Leading in Florida Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two new polls indicate that
Democrat Lawton Chiles is leading in his attempt to unseat
Republican Gov. Bob Martinez.
   A Florida Opinion Poll released Saturday by The New York Times
newspapers in Florida gave Chiles a 47-40 edge, with 13 percent
undecided. The margin of error was 4 percentage points.
   And a survey released Friday by Florida NBC affiliates showed
Chiles with a 44-38 lead over Martinez, with 18 percent undecided.
The margin of error was 4 percentage points.
   Martinez's campaign manager, J.M. ``Mac'' Stipanovich, said all
other polls indicate the race is neck-and-neck.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Oregon's Packwood Wants Out of Montana Senate Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. Bob Packwood of Oregon
doesn't want to be a part of Democratic Sen. Max Baucus'
re-election campaign.
   Packwood is being featured in Baucus commercials that defend his
voting record against allegations from GOP challenger Allen
Kolstad, the state's lieutenant governor.
   The ad is in response to one by Kolstad that alleged Baucus
voted for a $50 million tax break for Phillips Petroleum in 1986.
Packwood, former chairman of the Senate Taxation Committee, is
quoted as saying Kolstad is wrong and that Baucus wasn't
responsible for including the tax break in a bill.
   Elaine Franklin, Packwood's chief of staff, said she called
Baucus' campaign manager after seeing the ad Friday ``and said it
would be our preference that Sen. Packwood is not in this race.''
   Paul Risley, Baucus campaign spokesman, said the ad would
continue. And Kolstad spokesman Stuart Brown said Kolstad's
original ad also would continue.
   Franklin said she didn't know Packwood's letter about Kolstad's
allegations would be used in a TV commercial. However, she said
Packwood didn't hesitate to provide the statement.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Poll Gives Voinovich 13.5 Point Lead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican gubernatorial candidate George
Voinovich has a 13-point lead over Democratic Attorney General
Anthony J. Celebrezze Jr., according to a new poll.
   But both campaigns cast doubt on the Ohio Poll survey.
   ``I don't believe it. I know we're doing well, but I don't think
we're doing 13 points,'' said Voinovich, who served as mayor of
Cleveland for a decade.
   And Natalie Wymer, Celebrezze's deputy press secretary, called
the poll ``just not believable.''
   ``Our own internal polls for the same period of time show us
dead even,'' she said.
   The Ohio Poll is jointly sponsored by the Dayton Daily News, The
Cincinnati Post and University of Cincinnati. It was conducted by
the university's Institute for Policy Research.
   Results showed Voinovich was supported by 52.3 percent of the
likely voters surveyed, while Celebrezze drew the backing of 38.8
percent. Another 8.9 percent were undecided. The margin of error
was 3.5 percentage points.
</TEXT>
