<HEAD>Senate Republicans on the Offensive in 1990 Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The numbers say this election year should be a
good one for Democrats to strengthen their hold on the Senate. But
since candidates and not numbers win elections, it's the GOP that's
on the offensive.
   ``We have a better crop of challengers this time than we've ever
had,'' said Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., chairman of the National
Republican Senatorial Committee.
   ``I'd be happy and pleased and I think we would say we've done a
good job if we stay the same'' in Democratic strength, said Sen.
John Breaux, D-La., chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee.
   By tradition, an off-year election bodes well for the party that
doesn't control the White House. And from a distance, it looks like
this one should follow the pattern.
   Democrats have a 55-45 majority in the Senate, but the
Republicans have more seats at risk. Of the 34 Senate seats on the
line, the GOP must defend 18 and the Democrats 16.
   Three incumbent Republicans are retiring, heightening the
apparent Democratic opportunity.
   But seven months before the election, it appears the Democrats
have failed to recruit many top-flight candidates while the GOP has
succeeded. That gives Republicans hope they can narrow the
Democrats' majority this year and perhaps reclaim control of the
Senate in 1992.
   In all three cases where Republican senators are stepping down
this year, GOP House members have stepped forward as candidates and
are the early front-runners.
   In Colorado, where Sen. Bill Armstrong is retiring, Rep. Hank
Brown hopes to step into the breach. Popular Rep. Robert Smith is
running for the seat being vacated by Sen. Gordon Humphrey in New
Hampshire. And in Idaho, Rep. Larry Craig is seeking to succeed
Sen. James A. McClure.
   Four other House Republicans are taking the far riskier leap
into races against incumbent Democrats _ creating potentially the
hottest Senate contests in the nation.
   The Iowa Senate campaign already is steaming as Republican Rep.
Tom Tauke challenges incumbent Democrat Tom Harkin. In Illinois,
GOP Rep. Lynn Martin has had help from President Bush in her
challenge against Democratic Sen. Paul Simon.
   In Rhode Island, Republican Rep. Claudine Schneider is trying to
unseat a popular but aging Democratic Sen. Claiborne Pell. And in
Michigan, Republican Rep. Bill Schuette is in a primary fight
against conservative activist Clark Durant for the right to
challenge Democratic Sen. Carl Levin.
   Another close race is shaping up in Nebraska, where former
Republican Rep. Hal Daub, who failed in a Senate bid two years ago,
is challenging Democratic incumbent Sen. J. James Exon. Another
Democratic incumbent that Republicans consider vulnerable is Sen.
Max Baucus of Montana. The list of Republican challengers there
includes Lt. Gov. Allen Kolstad.
   Meanwhile, no Republican senators who are seeking re-election
appear to be in serious trouble so far. Poll results suggest that
GOP Sens. Jesse Helms in North Carolina and Mitch McConnell in
Kentucky are vulnerable, but potential Democratic challengers still
are fighting among themselves in both states.
   Although some House Democrats flirted with entering Senate
races, none did. And in several cases, popular present and former
state office holders passed up seemingly good opportunities to move
to Washington.
   The Democrats tried hard to recruit candidates ``but their
efforts just seemed to come up a little bit short,'' said political
analyst Charles Cook. Finding a good Senate candidate is mostly
luck of the draw and ``this time, the Republicans got all the
breaks,'' he said.
   The result is apparent security for the GOP _ even a slim chance
of taking control of the Senate if they can sweep all of the close
races _ while ``Democrats have too many seats close to the edge,''
Cook said.
   A 50-50 split would give Republicans control, because the
Republican vice president would break tie votes.
   If the Republicans trimmed the Democratic majority to less than
two or three seats after this election, the GOP would be in a good
position to retake the Senate in 1992 when 20 Democrats and only 14
Republicans face re-election.
   There is talk of two more races being added to the 34 scheduled
this fall.
   Hawaii Democrat Spark Matsunaga has cancer and must be brought
into the Senate chamber by wheelchair to vote. Although he has not
indicated he will resign, potential successors have been quietly
eyeing his seat.
   A Senate Ethics Committee investigation of Sen. Dave
Durenberger's personal finances has led to speculation that the
Minnesota Republican might resign if serious charges were brought.
   Breaux, who leads the Senate Democrats' campaign committee, said
his lack of Senate challengers from the House isn't the handicap
the Washington cognoscenti make it out to be.
   ``Who's to say that House members are better candidates than
people who are not from Washington and can run against the mistakes
and the problems that Washington is in fact responsible for?'' he
asked.
   Breaux acknowledged, though, that he's hoping for some upsets.
One race where he sees potential is Democratic businessman Ted
Muenster's bid to oust Republican Sen. Larry Pressler in South
Dakota.
   The Democratic drive to hold the line this year is fueled by the
specter of 1992.
   ``I'm running down the track looking over my left shoulder and
then I turn and look over my right shoulder,'' said Breaux, who
faces re-election himself in two years.
   Neither Breaux nor Nickles saw an overriding national theme in
this year's races.
   Breaux said the abortion issue could help Democrats in several
pro-choice states where the Republican candidate has an
anti-abortion stance, as is the case in Iowa and Michigan. It also
could give Democrats an upset, perhaps in New Hampshire or Oregon,
where anti-abortion incumbent Mark O. Hatfield is being challenged
by Democratic businessman Harry Lansdale.
   Nickles discounts abortion's role in the next election.
Republican gubernatorial losses in New Jersey and Virginia last
fall may have been due to anti-abortion stands because
``Republicans did a poor job responding,'' and that won't happen
this time, he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, April 9</NOTE>
</DOC>

