<HEAD>GOP Still Sees Potential for Senate Gains in November Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican hopes of slashing the Democrats'
55-45 Senate majority hinge on the potential for a voter earthquake
to shake things up in the final weeks before Election Day.
   Republicans so far have been unable to turn the electorate
against a swath of Democratic incumbents whom the GOP identified
earlier this year as potentially vulnerable.
   All but one Democratic incumbent is leading in the polls. But
Democrats concede the Republican claim that voters have been
distracted by the crisis in the Persian Gulf and are just starting
to focus on the races.
   ``Six weeks out, and voters are only now paying attention,''
said Anita Dunn, spokeswoman for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee. ``I don't think any lead right now is very meaningful.''
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., chairman of the National Republican
Senatorial Committee, recalled that in 1980 and 1986, the last two
years where the Senate changed parties, ``the races really didn't
close until the last three weeks.''
   The GOP is ``certainly within striking distance'' in many races
this year, even if the polls don't always show it, he said. The
list includes Iowa, Michigan, Illinois, Hawaii, Nebraska, Montana
and Rhode Island.
   If Republicans get most of the breaks, which Nickles says is
unlikely, they could pick up the five seats needed to wrest control
from the Democrats.
   But the GOP clearly would be satisfied with gaining just two or
three seats, which would make the Democrats especially vulnerable
in 1992, when many who barely won office in 1986 are up for
re-election for the first time.
   Currently, Hawaii Sen. Daniel Akaka is the only incumbent
Democrat who is behind in the polls, and not by much. Akaka was
appointed to the Senate earlier this year to fill the seat of the
late Spark Matsunaga.
   Akaka is running against his former House colleague, Republican
Rep. Pat Saiki.
   Iowa has been a brawl for months between Democratic Sen. Tom
Harkin and Republican Rep. Tom Tauke. Republicans say Tauke is
whittling away at Harkin's lead, but Democrats say Tauke was hurt
by the disclosure that he accepted a congressional pay raise he had
campaigned against. Tauke said he took the money, but later donated
it to charity.
   The GOP's heavy recruitment of candidates from the House of
Representatives hasn't worked so well in other cases.
   Michigan, Illinois and Rhode Island are states where the
Democratic incumbents have held tenaciously to leads in polls
despite tough opposition from GOP House members.
   In Michigan, incumbent Democrat Carl Levin was preferred by
voters 2-1 over Rep. Bill Schuette in a recent poll, despite an
aggressive television campaign by the Republican challenger.
   President Bush interceded to get Illinois Rep. Lynn Martin the
GOP nomination to challenge Sen. Paul Simon, but the Democrat has
maintained a solid lead in the polls.
   Rhode Island Rep. Claudine Schneider has proven statewide appeal
in that tiny state. But she's still struggling to chip away at the
popularity of incumbent Democratic Sen. Claiborne Pell.
   Earlier this year, Republicans considered Sen. Max Baucus,
D-Mont., as the most vulnerable of their targets. But Baucus has
climbed in the polls in recent weeks to a solid 25-point lead over
conservative Lt. Gov. Allen Kolstad.
   While disappointed that more hasn't happened in those races, the
GOP sees new opportunity in Massachusetts, where voters in the
primary threw out the Democratic Party slate for state officers.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., has been indirectly hurt. Previously
considered safe, Kerry suddenly is just barely ahead of challenger
Rappaport in the polls. Rappaport already has run a television ad
linking Kerry with unpopular Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   But Republicans may have trouble using the ``throw the rascals
out'' tactic in many of the states where they have been most
hopeful, since they recruited so many sitting or former members of
Congress as candidates.
   Democrats are confident Kerry will hold his seat, just as
Republicans are confident Jesse Helms of North Carolina will win,
even though he's in a dead heat in the polls with former Charlotte
mayor Harvey Gantt.
   Both sides point to longshot chances against the others'
incumbents in other states, and Democrats are behind but still hope
to grab one or more of the three seats where Republican incumbents
are retiring in Colorado, Idaho and New Hampshire.
   But perhaps the most unusual race of the year is one where both
parties concede the outcome - that Sen. J. Bennett Johnston, D-La.,
will win re-election.
   The big question is whether Johnston can capture 50 percent of
the vote in Louisiana's Oct. 6 open primary and avoid a runoff in
November with the sure second-place finisher - former Ku Klux
Klansman David Duke.
   Republicans are so worried that Duke will represent their party
on the ticket that they have virtually abandoned the campaign of
their chosen candidate, Ben Bagert, in hopes Johnston can avoid a
runoff.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 30</NOTE>
