<HEAD>Primary Candidates Head to the Wire in Nine States</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS new 8th graf, One Helms ad, to include details of
Helms ads</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Democrats Harvey Gantt and Mike
Easley, entering the closing hours of their Senate runoff primary,
are concentrating their fire on Republican Sen. Jesse Helms. But
across the continent, California Democrats are slamming each other.
   North Carolina and California are among nine states holding
primaries on Tuesday, the busiest day so far of the 1990 election
year. The other states are Alabama, Iowa, Mississippi, Montana, New
Jersey, New Mexico and South Dakota.
   As they entered the final 24 hours before voters cast their
ballots, candidates checked opinion polls, unleashed their final
television ads and tried to stir support with a closing round of
personal appearances.
   Two new polls of potential voter sentiment in the bitterly fought
race for the Democratic nomination for governor of California showed
former San Francisco Mayor Dianne Feinstein maintaining a lead over
state Attorney General John Van de Kamp.
   The Los Angeles Times poll said Feinstein had a 13-point lead _ a
gain of two points over a similar survey early in May. The poll gave
the former mayor 42 percent and Van de Kamp 29 percent. There were
29 percent still undecided or supporting one of the nine minor
candidates on the Democratic primary ballot.
   Mervin Field's California Poll, which gave Feinstein a slim 3
percent lead earlier this month, reported that margin had opened up
to 8 points over Van de Kamp, 42-34, in polling that concluded
Sunday. New polls also were out in Iowa and New Mexico.
   In North Carolina, Easley accused Helms of attacking him with
``personal character assassinations'' in radio ads. ``They are
personal and very negative,'' the Brunswick County prosecutor told
supporters Sunday.
   One Helms ad accuses Easley of waffling on the issues and another
suggests that he plea-bargained a drug case involving a campaign
contributor's son who was caught with nearly a pound of cocaine.
   Easley said he was countering with ads saying, ``This year North
Carolina must say no to Jesse Helms and mudslinging.''
   ``I think Charlotte people believed long before anyone else that
we are going to bring Jesse Helms home,'' Gantt told supporters
Sunday night in Charlotte, N.C.
   Abortion was the issue of the day in California where Sen. Pete
Wilson had only token opposition for the GOP nomination to succeed
fellow Republican George Deukmejian in the governor's office.
Deukmejian declined to seek a third term.
   Van de Kamp appeared on the steps of the Los Angeles County
Courthouse with Norma McCorvey, the ``Jane Roe'' of the landmark
U.S. Supreme Court's Roe vs. Wade abortion rights decision.
   ``I have no criticism of Mrs. Feinstein's record (on abortion),''
McCorvey said. ``But I believe John Van de Kamp is the candidate who
will do the most to protect a woman's right to choose. I trust John
Van de Kamp.''
   Feinstein also stressed her long support of abortion rights,
telling fund-raisers in West Hollywood that ``I believe that a woman
is best protected by another woman who believes in the right to
choose.''
   The two candidates were running television commercials harshly
attacking each other.
   Van de Kamp's commercials described Feinstein as a ``Republican
in Democratic clothing,'' while the former mayor's ads accused the
attorney general of refusing to ``talk about his own record.''
   Abortion also has been a major issue in Iowa's Democratic primary
for governor. The National Abortion Rights Action League endorsed
Iowa House speaker Don Avenson in a move designed to help him
against anti-abortion rival Tom Miller, the state attorney general.
Republican Gov. Terry Branstad is an abortion opponent.
   A new poll, published Sunday in the Des Moines Register, said
Avenson had moved into the lead with support from 32 percent of
those surveyed, compared with 25 percent for Miller. Former banker
John Chrystal was at 19 percent, and 20 percent said they were
undecided.
   The newspaper said the sampling was among 629 likely primary
voters and had a margin of error of 3.9 percent.
   ``It's breaking our way, obviously,'' said Avenson.
   In New Mexico, large fields were seeking the gubernatorial
nomination in both parties. Incumbent GOP Gov. Garrey Carruthers was
ineligible to seek re-election, but the person elected to succeed
him will be the first New Mexico governor allowed to serve two
successive terms.
   A new poll published Sunday in the Albuquerque Journal said state
Senate Minority Leader Les Houston and former legislator Frank Bond
each had the support of 29.2 percent of the registered Republicans
surveyed.
   On the Democratic side, former Gov. Bruce King had the backing of
42.7 percent, while state Attorney General Paul Bardacke was
supported by 31.5 percent.
   The poll was conducted for the Journal by Research and Polling
Inc. of Albuquerque, which surveyed 664 registered Democrats and 402
registered Republicans. It had a margin of error of plus or minus 4
percent for the Democrats and 5 percent for the Republicans.
   A large field was battling in Alabama for the Democratic
nomination to oppose GOP Gov. Guy Hunt, the first Republican to hold
that office since the post-Civil War Reconstruction period.
   Among the Democratic contenders was former Gov. Fob James who was
taped recently by a public television crew while telling a
Republican Party official that ``there ain't but one damn Goldwater
Republican in this race, and you know who that is.''
   An aide to James, a former Republican, said the remark was ``a
joke more than anything.''
   In Montana, four Republicans were vying for the nomination to
oppose Democratic Sen. Max Baucus.
   In Mississippi, Republican Sen. Thad Cochran was as good as
re-elected to a third term. He had no primary opposition and no
Democrat has filed to run against him in the fall.
   Democratic Sens. Bill Bradley of New Jersey and Howell Heflin of
Alabama had only token primary opposition. The same was true of
Republican Sens. Larry Pressler of South Dakota and Pete Domenici of
New Mexico.
   Gantt and Easley worked hard to get out their core supporters.
   ``There are a lot of voters out there, especially in the East,
that we ought to be able to pick up,'' Easley said while campaigning
in the eastern part of the state. ``If we have a big turnout in the
East, Mike Easley will win the runoff. If we don't it'll be real
close.''
   Gantt sought votes in the same region over the weekend,
especially in the northeast, which has a high percentage of black
voters who were critical in the May 8 primary when the former mayor
of Charlotte led a six-man field.
   But Gantt fell short of the 40 percent threshold he needed to
avoid a runoff and become the first black candidate for statewide
office in North Carolina this century.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

