<HEAD>Feinstein Buoyed By Polls In California Campaign's Final Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Former San Francisco mayor Dianne Feinstein got encouraging news
Monday from two new polls in the California governor's race as she
and scores of candidates played out the final hours of primary
campaigns in nine states.
   In the often nasty Democratic primary campaign, Feinstein
maintained a lead over state Attorney General John Van de Kamp in
the latest statewide surveys. For months the two candidates have
attacked each other on issues ranging from abortion and crime to who
could best handled the state's fiscal affairs.
   Other new polls showed close races Tuesday for gubernatorial
nominations in Alabama, Iowa and New Mexico. In North Carolina, a
runoff between two Democrats will determine who challenges
Republican Sen. Jesse Helms, while four Montana Republicans were
vying for the chance to run against Democratic Sen. Max Baucus.
   Baucus was among seven incumbent senators facing token primary
opposition at most on Tuesday.
   The others were Democrats Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Howell
Heflin of Alabama and Tom Harkin of Iowa, and Republicans Thad
Cochran of Mississippi, Pete Domenici of New Mexico and Larry
Pressler of South Dakota.
   Except for Cochran, who will have no Democratic opponent in
November, renomination isn't necessarily a free ticket to another
term.
   Harkin faces a tough re-election race against GOP Rep. Tom Tauke,
while Heflin and Pressler also are under challenge from potentially
strong opponents. Heflin's foe in November will be Republican Bill
Cabannis and Pressler will come up against Democrat Ted Muenster.
   With his outspoken conservative views, Helms attracts both
intense support and equally strong opposition. The Democrats, who
must decide between Harvey Gantt and Mike Easley for their nominee,
hope to capitalize on the latter in the general election campaign.
   Gantt led a six-candidate field in the May 8 primary but failed
to reached the 40 percent needed to avoid a runoff. The former mayor
of Charlotte is seeking to become the first black nominated for
statewide office in North Carolina.
   The race for the Democratic nomination for governor of Alabama
was headed for a runoff, with none of the five contenders likely to
get the 50 percent needed to win outright in the first round. The
top two finishers would be on the ballot for a runoff June 26 to
decide who challenges Republican Gov. Guy Hunt.
   A Birmingham News-Huntsville Times poll published Sunday said
former Gov. Fob James had the support of 26.1 percent, followed by
state Attorney General Don Siegelman with 25.6 percent, Rep. Ronnie
Flippo 20.5 percent, teacher-lobbyist Paul Hubbert 20.1 percent and
state Sen. Charles Bishop 3.3 percent. The poll had a margin of
error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
   The biggest 1990 prize is the California governor's office.
   Republican Gov. George Deukmejian is retiring after two terms and
the GOP recruited Sen. Pete Wilson to enter the race to succeed him.
Re-elected to the Senate in 1988 with 53 percent of the vote, Wilson
became the immediate favorite to keep the office in Republican hands.
   With the 1990 Census likely to give California six new House
seats starting with the 1992 election, control of the governor's
office could determine which party draws the new district lines.
Democrats already control both legislative chambers.
   In addition to targeting the governor's race, Republicans also
are sponsoring two ballot initiatives on redistricting in
California. One would take it out of the hands of the legislature,
the other would give the governor an absolute veto over any plan.
   A new Los Angeles Times poll said Feinstein had a 13-point lead _
a gain of two points over a similar survey early in May. The poll
gave the former mayor 42 percent and Van de Kamp 29 percent. There
were 29 percent still undecided or supporting one of the nine minor
candidates on the Democratic primary ballot. The survey had a 5
percentage point margin of error.
   Mervin Field's California Poll, which gave Feinstein a slim 3
percent lead earlier this month, reported that margin had opened up
to 8 points over Van de Kamp, 42-34, in polling that concluded
Sunday. It had a 3.5 percentage point margin of error.
   A new Iowa poll in the race for the Democratic nomination for
governor was published Sunday in theDes Moines Register and said
Iowa House Speaker Don Avenson had moved into the lead with support
from 32 percent of those surveyed, compared with 25 percent for
state Attorney General Tom Miller. Former banker John Chrystal was
at 19 percent, and 20 percent said they were undecided. The survey
had a margin of error of 3.9 percentage points.
   The winner of the Democratic primary will face Republican Gov.
Terry Branstad in the general election.
   In New Mexico, a new poll published Sunday in the Albuquerque
Journal said state Senate Minority Leader Les Houston and former
legislator Frank Bond each had the support of 29.2 percent of the
registered Republicans asked their preference in the GOP
gubernatorial primary.
   On the Democratic side, former Gov. Bruce King had the backing of
42.7 percent, while state Attorney General Paul Bardacke was
supported by 31.5 percent. The New Mexico survey had a margin of
error of 4 percentage points on the Democratic side and 5 percentage
points on the GOP side.
</TEXT>
