<HEAD>UNDATED: since 1984.</HEAD>
<HEAD>INDIANA (12)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In Dan Quayle's home state, an Indianapolis Star poll published
Oct. 31 showed Bush with a 57 percent to 36 percent lead.
   In a bitter and costly governor's race, however, Democrat Evan
Bayh, son of former Sen. Birch Bayh, held a 54-40 lead over
Republican Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz in a Star poll. Bayh is the son of
former Sen. Birch Bayh, who was defeated in 1980 by Quayle.
   Through mid-October, Bayh had raised $3.2 million for a tough
television campaign that attacked tax increases during the Mutz's
years of service with retiring Gov. Robert D. Orr, and criticizing
Mutz for his role in extending state aid to a Subaru-Isuzu car and
truck plant. Mutz, who raised $3 million, said Bayh lacks
experience, distorts the facts and, on the Subaru-Isuzu issue, has
pandered to racial prejudices.
   Republican Sen. Richard G. Lugar, seeking a third term, has held
50-point leads over Democrat Jack Wickes in the last two Star polls.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IOWA (8)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis has an advantage in a traditionally Republican state.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>KANSAS (7)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis has been within striking distance all fall and Democrats
hoped that the slumping farm economy would put votes in their
column. However, a Kansas City Times poll published Oct. 29 said
Bush led 45 percent to 33 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>KENTUCKY (9)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In a state where Democrats hold a 2-to-1 advantage in
registration, Bush led 53 percent to 38 percent in a poll published
Oct. 30 by The Courier-Journal of Louisville.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>LOUISIANA (10)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Democrats had hoped that a prolonged recession triggered by the
collapse of oil prices would spell victory for Dukakis. However,
Bush has led in every poll taken since the conventions, with a
14-point margin in the latest conducted by the University of New
Orleans.
   Gov. Buddy Roemer, a Democrat, said he would vote for Dukakis but
skirted campaign duties, saying his time was needed for a special
legislative session in October.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MAINE (4)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush, who has a summer home at Kennebunkport, leads here.
   Sen. George J. Mitchell, a Democrat, has raised $8 for every
dollar contributed to Republican challenger Jasper S. Wyman. Wyman,
head of the conservative Maine Christian Civic League, entered the
race after more established Republicans refused. Mitchell heavily
favored.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MARYLAND (10)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The presidential race was close with a slight advantage to Bush.
   Sen. Paul S. Sarbanes, a Democrat, was favored to win a third
term.
   Opponents of gun control forced a referendum on a new state law
that creates a nine-member board to determine which handguns can be
sold in the state and which will be banned. The National Rifle
Association said it would spend between $4 million and $5 million to
defeat a bill that it said could make Maryland the first state to
ban the sale of all handguns.
   Late polls showed voters favoring the law by a margin of 10
points, though that gap has been shrinking.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MASSACHUSETTS (13)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush gave Dukakis a scare in his home state, pulling even in
early September polls. However, the governor bounced back to a
10-point lead in new surveys.
   Presidential politics overshadowed the only other statewide
contest, a mismatch for U.S. Senate between 26-year veteran Edward
M. Kennedy and political newcomer Joe Malone, a Republican. Malone,
33, presented himself as a conservative alternative to Kennedy's
``1960s liberalism.'' Polls suggested that Kennedy would be
re-elected by 2-to-1.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MICHIGAN (20)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A consistently close presidential race has leaned toward Bush in
the final days, but Gov. James Blanchard, who is working hard for
Dukakis, contends that Bush's support was soft.
   Sen. Donald Riegle, a Democrat from Flint, had a walkover race
against Republican challenger Jim Dunn, a former congressman, and
Riegle has devoted increasing time to campaigning for Dukakis.
   Dunn became so deperate for funds that he sued the Republican
National Committee, seeking $439,000 he said had been promised, but
the suit was dismissed.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MINNESOTA (10)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Democrats won this state by 3,761 votes in 1984, when favorite
son Walter Mondale was the nominee, and Dukakis will probably pull
out a similar narrow win.
   In the U.S. Senate race, Democratic Minnesota Attorney General
Hubert H. Humphrey III trailed in his attempt to win the seat once
held by his father. A recent Star Tribune poll showed 10-year
veteran Republican Sen. Dave Durenberger leading 53 percent to 42
percent.
   Durenberger, smarting from Humphrey's incessant attacks on his
voting record involving issues such as Social Security, Medicare,
health care and drug programs, withdrew his own negative television
ads for the last two weeks of the campaign. He challenged Humphrey
to do the same; Humphrey instead proposed to suspend all TV ads if
Durenberger would debate him three times every day. The offer was
not accepted.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MISSISSIPPI (7)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush has built a solid lead after Dukakis failed to generate
enthusiasm among black voters.
   In the race to succeed Democrat John C. Stennis in the Senate,
House Minority Leader Trent Lott holds a lead over Democrat Wayne
Dowdy. Dowdy has a reputation for finshing fast, and Lott has
stepped up a series of sweeps through the state coupled with an
expensive advertising blitz. Dowdy concentrated on personal
appearances in rural areas.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MISSOURI (11)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Republicans hope Bush can ride the coattails of Sen. John
Danforth and Gov. John Ashcroft, who are both far ahead in their
re-election campaigns. The latest statewide poll showed the race to
be a dead heat.
   Democrats say Rep. Richard Gephardt will face no trouble
defeating Republican Mark ``Thor'' Hearne, who has accused Gephardt
for neglecting his St. Louis district while seeking the Democratic
presidential nomination.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MONTANA (4)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Montana's ailing economy gave hope to Democrats, but a poll for
the Great Falls Tribune, published Oct. 30, showed Bush favored 49
percent to 34 percent.
   With Gov. Ted Schwinden deciding not to seek a third term,
Republicans believe they have their best chance in 20 years to win
the governor's office.
   Democrat Thomas Judge, 54, who was governor from 1973-81, has
published an elaborate economic development plan and made it the
cornerstone of his campaign. Republican Stan Stephens, 59, a former
state senator, has been on the defensive against Judge's attacks on
his conservative voting record. The Tribune poll found the race tied.
   The same poll showed Democratic Sen. John Melcher supported by 48
percent compared to 34 percent for Republican Conrad Burns. The GOP
hopes for an upset.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NEBRASKA (5)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Nebraska hasn't voted for the Democratic presidential candidate
since 1964, and isn't expected to break the pattern. But Sen. David
Karnes, a Republican appointed to his job in 1987, has trailed
Democrat Bob Kerrey in every public poll taken since the race began.
   Kerrey, a Medal of Honor winner who served one term as governor,
has mostly ignored Karnes.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NEVADA (4)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis pulled his top paid staffers out of Nevada and his state
campaign director, Joe Johnson, conceded ``we can't win.''
   Democratic Gov. Dick Bryan downplayed the significance of
Dukakis' white flag and predicted he would defeat Republican Sen.
Chic Hecht. The Senate race remained a tossup, with Bryan claiming a
lead of 10 percent or more and Hecht releasing his own polls showing
only a 2-point edge for the governor.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NEW HAMPSHIRE (4)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A Republican state. Bush holds a 2-to-1 advantage.
   In the race to succeed Gov. John Sununu, Rep. Judd Gregg faces
Democrat Paul McEachern, who made the Seabrook nuclear power plant
the key issue in his losing gubernatorial bid in 1986. This year
McEachern has targeted a broader range of issues and pegged Gregg _
a four-term congressman _ as a candidate for the privileged and
moneyed interests. Gregg, calling himself a fiscal conservative, has
denounced McEachern as a ``Massachusetts-style liberal.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NEW JERSEY (16)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The latest poll by the Eagleton Institute of Politics and The
Star-Ledger of Newark showed Bush 14 percentage points ahead.
   Republicans hope Bush can also carry Peter Dawkins to victory
against Democratic Sen. Frank Lautenberg in one of the nation's most
bitter campaigns. In television ads, Dawkins has accused his
opponent of being willing to do anything for money, while Lautenberg
accused the Republican of poisoning California's environment when he
commanded an Army base there.
   Lautenberg still leads.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NEW MEXICO (5)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush holds a 10-point lead here after gaining the support of many
Hispanics.
   Republican Steve Schiff, meanwhile, has pulled away from Democrat
Tom Udall, son of former Interior Secretary Stewart Udall of
Arizona, in their House race. Both men are former prosecutors, and
have criticized each other's policies regarding plea bargaining in a
campaign marked with negative advertising.
   Sen. Jeff Bingaman, a Democrat, is heavily favored over
Republican state Sen. Bill Valentine.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NEW YORK (36)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush fading after an early scare for Dukakis in a traditionally
Democratic state.
   Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan appeared headed to an
easy third-term victory against little-known lawyer Robert McMillan.
   McMillan has derided Moynihan as an ineffectual windbag. Moynihan
has ignored him and holds a 40-plus point lead.
</TEXT>
