<HEAD>Philippines Facing Serious Drug Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippines may become another
Colombia if anti-narcotics agencies cannot stop the increasingly
powerful drug rings operating in this country, a senator said today.
   ``Precisely, if we do not do something about this, there might
come a time when we will see the spectacle of the Philippines
becoming like Colombia, where drug lords even have armies,
helicopters, planes and even tanks,'' said Sen. Alberto Romulo.
   Romulo made the statement during a public hearing on last week's
report given by Sen. Ernesto Herrera alleging that at least 17
military officials are protecting drug syndicates.
   Maj. Gen. Ramon Montano, chief of the Philippine Constabulary,
admitted during the hearing that there are military men involved in
drug rings, but he said officials are doing their best to weed them
out.
   At least 40 officers have been ousted since Herrera's report and
assigned to combat units fighting communist guerrillas in the
countryside, Montano added.
   He said the drug problem has grown swiftly in the last few
years. Most drug syndicates operating in Asia's so-called ``Golden
Triangle'' of Burma, Laos and Thailand use the Philippines as a
relay point to Australia, the United States, Italy, Iran and some
Asian countries, he said.
   A total of 2,543 people were arrested for various drug-related
offenses last year, and 1,884 were arrested from January to
September this year, Montano said.
   But Sen. Romulo said most of those arrested and convicted were
small-time pushers, and none of the three major local drug groups'
leaders or their top managers has been arrested.
   Col. Virgilio David, chief of the Constabulary's Narcotics
Command, said he plans to change men under his command as often as
possible to prevent them from fraternizing with drug ring members.
   ``The temptation is just too great for soldiers whose average
salary is about 80 pesos ($3.60) a day,'' David said.
   During the hearing, Herrera played the first of at least 15
tapes of interviews with drug pushers, military and police officers
who gave names of officers involved in corruption involving the
drug trade.
